question:
Suppose that $A=\left( 
 \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 1 & 3 \\ 
0 & 0 & 5  \\ 
-1 & -2 & 1  \\ 
3 & 1 & 2 \end{array} \right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 1 & 0 \\ 
2 & 1 & 1 \\ 
1 & 1 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$, and $C=\left(  \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 2 & 0  \\ 
2 & 4 & 1  \\ 
3 & 6 & 2  \\ 
-4 & -8 & 1  \end{array}
\right)$.

Which matrix has the rank $2$ ?

Find $M^2+(A^T\cdot B)^{-1}$, where $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 3 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-2 & 4 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$, and $M=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
7 & 2 & 1 \\
-1 & 3 & 0  \\
2 & 0 & -2 \end{array}
\right)$.

Suppose that $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
-2  & -1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 1 & 2\\
2  & 1 & -2\end{array}
\right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
4  & 1 & 0\end{array}
\right)$, and $C=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
0  & 3 & -1\end{array}
\right)$. Find $X$ if $X\cdot A-B=C$.

Find the real values of $m$ for which the following set of vectors $V=\left( \begin{array}{r}  
1\\ 
2 \\
m \end{array}
\right)$, $Z=\left( \begin{array}{r}  
1\\ 
-1 \\
m \end{array}
\right)$, and
$W=\left( \begin{array}{r}  
3\\ 
m+2 \\
1 \end{array}
\right)$ is linearly independent.

Let $M=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
1  & 0 & 2 \\ 
-1 & 1 & 0\\
0  & 2 & 1\end{array}
\right)$ and $f(x)=x^2-2x+3$. Find $f(M).$
